{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-research-js","path":"/research/braillesc/","result":{"pageContext":{"id":"braillesc","fields":{"researchDescription":{"childMarkdownRemark":{"html":"<p>In Making the Digital Humanities More Open, MITH will work with BrailleSC to undertake its second stage of development by designing and deploying a WordPress‐based accessibility tool that will create braille content for end-users who are blind or low vision. Extending the use of Anthologize—a free and open source plug‐in for WordPress that currently translates any RSS text into PDF, ePub, HTML, or TEI—MITH and the BrailleSC team will develop braille output for the tool.\nAs a result, BrailleSC will not only make it easy for content creators to convert a text into braille, thereby extending humanities content to hundreds of thousands of visually disabled readers, but will also experiment with making braille available visually through the WordPress interface.</p>"}},"researchExcerpt":{"childMarkdownRemark":{"html":"<p>BrailleSC makes it easy for content creators to convert a text into braille, thereby extending humanities content to hundreds of thousands of visually disabled readers. BrailleSC also experiment with making braille available visually through the WordPress interface.</p>"}},"image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"constrained","backgroundColor":"#f8f8f8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/mith-static/static/8d94c53c58a94f97b4b43eeaa79dd063/241ed/header_braillesc.png","srcSet":"/mith-static/static/8d94c53c58a94f97b4b43eeaa79dd063/f6f42/header_braillesc.png 350w,\n/mith-static/static/8d94c53c58a94f97b4b43eeaa79dd063/4bade/header_braillesc.png 700w,\n/mith-static/static/8d94c53c58a94f97b4b43eeaa79dd063/241ed/header_braillesc.png 1400w","sizes":"(min-width: 1400px) 1400px, 100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/mith-static/static/8d94c53c58a94f97b4b43eeaa79dd063/5e4a8/header_braillesc.webp 350w,\n/mith-static/static/8d94c53c58a94f97b4b43eeaa79dd063/47a4a/head